english:
  title: Joint Memorial from the Hongmun and Yemun Academies
  author: Chae Su
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty,

    We humbly submit that recently, when rain mixed with dust fell upon the earth, you issued an edict seeking counsel on its meaning. We have carefully examined the historical records and find that some have called this portent a sign of worthy men being obscured, others a sign of the people being burdened, and still others a sign that the unworthy consume state stipends. Considering these interpretations, rain mixed with dust is no trivial matter. Since calamities do not manifest without reason, it is fitting that Your Majesty should contemplate this seriously and seek to understand the current abuses of government in order to answer Heaven's reproach.

    Today, both at court and among the common people, many subtle matters bring harm to governance and suffering to the people. Though it is difficult to speak of all of them, we should address the urgent before the gradual, the great before the small. Would it be right to discourse upon tigers and wolves while leaving foxes in their den?

    We have heard that on the twenty-first of this month, the Classics Lecturer and the Censorate presented several matters for approval, all of which received your sanction. Yet the Chief Eunuch Lim Sa-hong argued against these decisions outside the court and, using official business as pretext, personally entered to present a secret memorial. The words Sa-hong spoke are the language of ancient treacherous ministers, while Your Majesty's response embodies the teachings of sage emperors. We cannot contain our joy in prostrating before Your Majesty, nor our anguish regarding Sa-hong.

    In ancient times, sages understood that when calamities arise, Heaven demonstrates its benevolence toward the ruler by urging him to cultivate his person and reform his conduct. Though solar and lunar eclipses follow fixed patterns, the Sage recorded them in the Spring and Autumn Annals as great portents—thus no ruler can treat such matters as commonplace. There are calamities of Heaven, calamities of Earth, and calamities born of human affairs. The sun, moon, stars, wind, rain, water, fire, insects, and plants—all anomalies in these things—signal changes below and bring harm to the people, shaking their hearts and minds. All such things are calamities. The sage kings of old were ever vigilant and cautious, never neglecting to heed even small calamities. How much more so when the calamities encountered are as these?

    The heart of a loyal minister fears only that his ruler will not take calamities and portents seriously—as when the Minister Wei remonstrated with Emperor Xuan about rebellious winds and rains. The heart of a treacherous minister fears only that his ruler will learn to dread calamities—as when Yang Guozhong deceived the Ming Emperor by claiming that prolonged rains do not harm the crops. Your Majesty possesses the virtue of Yao and Tang—their caution and fear—yet Sa-hong cannot guide you as those two sages were guided, but rather wishes to guide you as the Ming Emperor was led. Our anguish knows no bounds.

    Consider the present situation: the rice has barely sprouted, the barley has not yet been harvested, and the year's fortune cannot be foretold. Yet Sa-hong declares, "The autumn harvest approaches with promise; the barley will be excellent," spreading words of abundance to please Your Majesty. Scarcely had the dust rain ceased when fires broke out in people's homes, consuming hundreds of dwellings. Calamities and portents have occurred repeatedly. Your Majesty's sacred person has shown appropriate concern, and the Censorate requested a prohibition on wine. Yet Sa-hong responded: "Auspicious clouds, dark vapors, falling stars, and dust rain—these are merely the workings of fate. Houses are clustered together; people were careless with fire; fierce winds spread the flames. There is nothing strange in this. There is no need for Your Majesty to reform your conduct or institute a wine prohibition."

    This is the doctrine of Wang Anshi's "three things not worthy of concern." Sa-hong first predicted autumn abundance to curry favor with Your Majesty, then dismissed both celestial changes and human suffering as unworthy of fear, thereby deceiving Your Majesty. We cannot discern whether Sa-hong counts himself loyal or treacherous, or whether he regards Your Majesty as a sage ruler or one clouded in judgment. Our anguish is boundless.

    Regarding the Way of Culture and Martial Virtue: this Way cannot be abandoned. Yet emperors establish Culture through moral virtue and righteousness, and Martial Virtue through commanding authority and decisive courage. We have never heard that Emperor Wu of Han grappling with fierce beasts, or Emperor Yang of Sui composing flowery verses, exemplified Culture and Martial Virtue.

    Recently, Your Majesty composed poetry frequently. When our colleague Gyeong-yu presented a memorial stating that rulers should not display their arts to the people, Your Majesty agreed deeply and ordered the plaques removed. When Your Majesty recently observed archery competitions and shot arrows alongside your relatives, the Censorate similarly observed that the sun cannot descend to mingle with ten thousand things, nor can a ruler compete with his ministers for victory. This argument also contains wisdom.

    Yet Sa-hong then said: "If the ruler composes poetry, the Censorate says it is improper. If the ruler shoots arrows personally, they say it is improper. Then what of the Way of Culture and Martial Virtue? Should it be abandoned?" With these words, he sought to provoke Your Majesty's anger, using this merely as a technique to exclude the Censorate. Yet by calling poetry composition and personal archery the exemplification of Your Majesty's Culture and Martial Virtue, how contemptibly he regards Your Majesty!

    In recent times, the conduct of scholars has deteriorated. In their pursuit of wealth and luxury, extravagance has grown excessive. In their building of mansions, they compete in splendor. The government established regulations on these structures, yet the law has not been enforced—beginning with those of high station. The residence of the Junior Princess, finding the regulation too restrictive, was constructed with seven beams and four pillars—structures that imitate the palace and rival even the auxiliary halls, indeed surpassing them. All in the capital, men and women alike, were startled and amazed.

    When the great minister Jeong Chang-son, Hong Eung, and members of the Censorate raised this extravagance in the Classics Lecture and requested fixed measurements be established, Your Majesty immediately acceded to their words. Thus the law of measurements arose from the Junior Princess's residence—which is the home of Sa-hong's son Gwang-jae.

    Sa-hong then became haughty and arrogant, showing no shame. He immediately presented a memorial stating: "The spacing regulations have already been established; there is no need to fix measurements further. Treacherous schemes are difficult to measure; even if such a law is established, there will inevitably be those who devise cunning ways to circumvent it." By "treacherous schemes difficult to measure" and "cunning ways to circumvent," he was describing his own son's residence. Alas! Your Majesty wished to establish law to eliminate such presumption, yet Sa-hong dared to argue against it and prevent its implementation—all because of his own son's house. His disdain for Your Majesty and his utter shamelessness are profound. Our anguish is unbearable.

    The Censorate are the ears and eyes of the ruler, the vital force of the state. Should the channels of speech be blocked, the ears and eyes are obscured and the vital force withers. How long can such a state endure? Therefore, a sage ruler must open his heart to listen, receive remonstrators with peaceful countenance, and allow all to speak their minds fully. When their words are apt, adopt them; when they miss the mark, do not punish them. In this way, the observation and hearing of the whole realm becomes the ruler's own observation and hearing. Nothing in the outer realm remains unknown, and treacherous ministers find no opportunity for scheming.

    But if a ruler cannot bear the bitter medicine of loyal words—if he initially feigns acceptance but later cannot endure it, rebuking counselors for trivialities or blaming them for insincerity—then under the thunderous authority of the throne, speech becomes culpable and silence the path to safety. Who then would dare open his mouth with words of healing salve? In such circumstances, inside and outside become divided; the court becomes distant as a thousand leagues, the outer realm as ten thousand. Beyond the palace gates, the welfare and suffering of the people, the advantages and disadvantages to the state—the ruler knows none of it. Then treacherous ministers seize their chance, toy with power and favor, expel the upright, gather their factions, and bring great calamity.

    Since Your Majesty's accession, you have received remonstrance as a flowing stream receives tributaries. Though their words sometimes miss the mark, none have been punished. The officials and people of the Three Kingdoms rejoice and celebrate, believing Your Majesty a ruler unborn in ages, eagerly anticipating a reign of great peace.

    Yet Sa-hong secretly memorialized: "Recently the Censorate speak too freely on matters. Their words should not all be followed. When their words miss the mark, you should show them signs of reproof." Alas! These are the words of a ruined state—words once spoken by Zhao Gao, Li Linfu, and Niu Sengru. That Sa-hong dares speak such words to Your Majesty reveals his heart all too clearly.

    The state does not entrust the affairs of the Three Excellencies and Six Ministries to them, but rather concentrates all power in the Chancellery. Sa-hong serves as its head; thus much of the realm's authority rests in his hands. He wishes to monopolize power and authority, to act with utter shamelessness. Yet he fears those who might criticize him. He seeks first to cloud Your Majesty's wisdom, so that the Censorate dare not speak his faults. Scheming without success, he waited for his opportunity. Recently, when Your Majesty observed archery repeatedly, the Censorate requested a wine prohibition and spoke of the impropriety of shooting in pairs. Sa-hong, with the mind of a petty man, presumed to read Your Majesty's heart, assuming you were wearied by their importuning. Thus he seized the moment, secretly memorialized to exclude the Censorate, and sought to provoke Your Majesty to test his intentions.

    We greatly rejoice that Your Majesty's response embodies the words of Yao and Shun. Yet we regret that you did not immediately command his punishment, to satisfy the indignation of your ministers and people. We humbly believe that Your Majesty's wisdom and sagacity clearly discern right from wrong. How could you be like the Ming Emperor, who recognized Li Linfu's treachery yet could not bring himself to remove him? That you have not yet removed Sa-hong—are you perhaps waiting, expecting the Censorate and attendants to speak further?

    Kim Su-on is a man of perversity and depravity who, though serving as Chancellor, wished to shave his head and leave home to follow a teaching that denies both father and ruler. Clearly, such a man cannot enter the Gate of the Sage nor sit in the Hall of Enlightenment to participate in solemn rites. When the Censorate remonstrated against this, Your Majesty accepted their words with favor. This truly reflects your noble determination to cast out heterodoxy and honor orthodoxy.

    Yet Sa-hong then said the Censorate were wrong, implying Su-on was acceptable to attend banquets. We believe Sa-hong did not speak thus to defend Su-on, but solely to exclude the Censorate from his councils.

    We, An Chim, Gyeong-yu, and others once served together with Sa-hong in the Censorate. Sa-hong would say to us in private: "When there are matters to present, there is no need to consult with colleagues. You may present memorials individually at the Classics Lecture or court audience." We followed this counsel, presenting memorials individually and later reporting to our colleagues. Sa-hong would approve. Yet when An Chim and Gu Ja-pyeong discussed Sa-hong's son's residence, Sa-hong grew angry. He went to persuade Chief Censor Yi Sung-won to convene both branches of the Censorate in the audience chamber, where they collectively censured An Chim for presenting memorials individually and simultaneously reproached him regarding his son's residence.

    Sa-hong's design was that, once censured, An Chim would be demoted by precedent, thus eliminating his rival in one sweep. Fortunately, Your Majesty's wisdom prevailed, and we were separated from Sa-hong at that time, allowing us to serve in the Classics Lecture until today. When Your Majesty personally questioned these events, Sa-hong sought to conceal his tracks by citing this "agreement" to deceive your wisdom. But if such an agreement truly existed, why would it not be enforced by his own office? Why would he need both branches to convene together in a single chamber? Since ancient times, have the two branches ever sat together in joint censure and called it an agreement? This is merely Sa-hong's deception of Your Majesty—a technique to exclude all who oppose him. His wickedness knows no restraint; he fears no public opinion and treats the court with utter contempt.

    Truly, since the founding of this dynasty, there has been no treachery like this. Yet men, fearing his power, dare not question his conduct. Shortly after we were separated from him, Your Majesty again appointed Sa-hong to a position of influence. It seems Your Majesty has not yet fully awakened to his true nature.

    Since ancient times, when rulers first employ small men, they do not knowingly do so as small men. Rather, they believe them talented and virtuous, worthy of confidence and trust. Some have mistaken great treachery and sycophancy for honesty and appointed such men to great power. When a loyal and passionate minister, unable to sit idle, presents a memorial of remonstrance, the ruler may regard him as one who criticizes superiors from below—improper conduct. Great ministers may dismiss him as one who seeks fame through feigned rectitude. And the treacherous minister himself, rather than examining his own conduct, turns instead to call the remonstrator suspicious, fraudulent, and scheming. By a hundred clever deceits, he clouds the ruler's wisdom, until the loyal voice finds no path to the throne. Thus the realm descends into ruin.

    We observe that Sa-hong is sinister and dissolute, employing his schemes without restraint. Outwardly stern and rigorous, he is inwardly treacherous and sycophantic. All the characteristics of ancient small men are gathered in him. Your Majesty does not perceive this; your trust in him is excessive. Thus Sa-hong believes his position secure, asking "Who would dare speak against me?" His shamelessness grows yet greater. He seeks to peddle his wiles, daring even before the sage ruler to declare that celestial calamities and human suffering are not worthy of fear, that the Censorate's words should not be heeded. Does he truly believe Your Majesty ignorant of ancient and modern history, unable to distinguish right from wrong in the human heart? Clearly, Your Majesty holds no place in his calculations; his deception is complete. Our anguish knows no bounds.

    Furthermore, Sa-hong's father, Won Jun, was treacherous and corrupt beyond compare in his time. His shameful conduct and evil deeds are recorded from the previous reign. He rose through conjuring tricks combined with literary skill, eventually entering the court and attending the Classics Lecture. His son became head of the Chancellery; his grandson married a princess. Internal and external connections multiplied; power and influence burned like flame. Men without virtue followed the wind of his advancement; men of insight lamented without ceasing.

    We, serving humbly as attendants, have witnessed Your Majesty's Heaven-bestowed sagacity and learning of perfect unity. If assisted by a capable and virtuous minister, the governance of Yao and Shun could surely be achieved. Yet such cunning and malevolent men have taken root in positions of power, flattering and ingratiating themselves, leading Your Majesty astray. Our anguish is boundless.

    We humbly believe that though we cannot point precisely to what deed summoned these calamities, the historical records speak of the unworthy consuming state stipends and worthy men being obscured as signs of such things—we fear this applies to such men. The burdening of the people as a sign—we suspect this too stems from the Junior Princess's residence. That such men should exist in an age of sage rule, with none daring to speak against them—is this not cause for fear? We truly regret that Confucius did not recognize Zai Yu's nature, that the Four Villains existed in Yao's time.

    The ancients said: "Only the benevolent man can banish and disperse the small men, sending them to the four barbarian lands, that they may not dwell in the Middle Kingdom."

    We humbly entreat Your Majesty: doubt not in casting out the treacherous. Banish and exile Won Jun and his son to answer the hopes of your people, to respond to Heaven's reproach, and to serve as a warning to treacherous and sycophantic ministers lacking in loyalty. We all grasp the historian's brush, intending to record these truths completely for transmission to ten thousand ages. Yet we fear that power and position will not be moved; we worry about slander and calamity. If we do not lay this before Your Majesty, then our sin against the state would be immeasurable.

    We dare thus to present this memorial, unable to contain our urgent sentiments.
  footnotes:
    - Rain mixed with dust (雨土) was regarded in traditional East Asian political thought as a portent signaling Heaven's displeasure with the ruler's governance, often interpreted as a call for moral and administrative reform.
    - The Chief Eunuch Lim Sa-hong represents a powerful court official whose influence and corruption threaten the proper functioning of government, particularly by attempting to suppress the Censorate's ability to remonstrate.
    - The "three things not worthy of concern" refers to Wang Anshi's controversial philosophy during the Northern Song dynasty, which rationalized away calamities as natural phenomena requiring no governmental response or moral reform.
    - The architectural regulations concern regulations limiting the size and grandeur of private residences to prevent the appearance of impropriety; Sa-hong's opposition protects his son's extravagantly constructed house.
    - Yi Sung-won and the joint censure represents the manipulation of bureaucratic procedure to suppress legitimate remonstrance by making individual memorial-presenting appear to violate protocol.
